This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the connection to common virus variants does not work as much as one of the existing medicines.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, patients can continue to live and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your dose is accompanied by a whole range of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus proliferation also results in the development of resistance viruses that are no longer effective.
The work of the experts of three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to how to deal with the virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances known as metalocarborans are active on the protein responsible for the proliferation of HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in a different way than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come to new 'improved' compounds prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metal-carborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two versatile cages, which consist of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are coupled by a metal-atom, in this case cobalt.
Tasty and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by HIV protease, there would be no mature infection virus particles.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the virus's proliferation in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute for Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease has been tested in the reagent glass, including their persistent (resistant) variants produced by HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as for the clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants, against which the used medicinal products are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its other characteristics, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical design, makes the Metalocarborans an interesting link for further research on the development of effective medicines against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the laboratory for structural biology of the Institute for Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute for Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
