A Change in the Course in the Ageing China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters that gave them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "A baby more means a grave more."
These lessons have taught them so well that, as government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change the course this summer due to the low birth rate and the ageing population, and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their answer was direct and final: "No way."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There is nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a head of staff with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has brought about two generations of notorious, disgraced single children, who are lovingly called "little emperors," a population crisis in the country is emerging.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UNO
This is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-old and older people accounted for almost 22 percent of the registered population of Shanghai, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai city population and family planning mission, said that couples of childbearing age must have babies to "help reduce the ratio of the ageing population and alleviate the labour shortages of the future."
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the developed countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
In the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial provision that the ruling Communist Party has introduced to this day.
Married couples who are in breach of this policy must expect huge fines - up to their three-fold annual salary in some regions - and discrimination in their workplace.
Chinese state representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural resources could be avoided, while human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had sex-elective abortions, resulting in an unnatural high ratio between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude to one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife have been single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many hard slogans was reduced.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the University of Beijing's Institute of Population Research, said that government representatives have recently even discussed more radical changes, for example, to allow couples to have two children with a partner being a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters who taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for the authorisation.
The city administration has sent out city employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and to push information sheets under the doors.
She also asked for psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not very encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outdoor areas of Shanghai said that there is an upswing in the applications of couples who want a second child after the launch of the campaign, the urban districts do not report any change.
In the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are received per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that, despite the campaign, the expected number of births in the city in 2010 will still be about 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai community of Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want to have children.
They want to give their first the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this was also legally allowed.
But, like many Chinese, they have only a small health and life insurance policy of the government.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West wrongly rate one-child policy as a human rights issue, Yang said, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yeah, we're being robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem, however, is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of staff, said she only wanted a child because she was an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone take care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and do not really want to. "
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it unblatantly.
For middle-class parents with a double career, through which the birth rate is falling, he said, it turns to be successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The age group of the 20-39 year-olds today grew up to see their parents fighting during the early days of the Chinese Capitalism experiment and they do not want such a life for themselves, he said.
Also a single child, he said, poses huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the room question -- "You have to change your apartment" -- and life planning -- "If the child is 9 months old, you have to have a resume for the best pre-school."
Most of his friends are ready to go through this once, said Chen, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to have achieved a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group designs emission reduction plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference - which has so far been characterised by wild poses and mutual accusations - once again focused on Friday on the publication of a document that will record an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrial nations having to bear the greatest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has identified both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, as next week more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, formulated by a UN working group specifically for this purpose, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrial and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of the global temperature increase that policy-makers would support.
The process is given great flexibility, said John Coequyt, leading representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has put together a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what the UN's leading climate change representative, Yvo de Boer, called "the big deal."
It shows the ground plan of a possible agreement where the industrial nations would together reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given the talks on Friday a boost through its commitment to provide 3.6 billion US dollars a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from the master of floods and droughts to the prevention of deforestation.
The Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that the talks had determined last week.
The US Climate Commissioner Todd Stern has rejected formulations that call for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging countries, if they are not financed by the industrialised countries.
This train announced that the Obama government has a tougher line with China than the Bush government representative, not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without larger emerging economies standing up and taking action, Stern, who also complained that the text would not go far enough, would ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave his statement one hour after the statement of the Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister He Yafei, who said that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or that it was "highly irresponsible" of him that he said at the beginning of the week that the United States would not help China financially to master global warming.
The fact that the future economic direction of the great world powers is at stake has been broken down both within the industrial nations and between the industrial nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle is about saving individual economies, as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous measures.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegation from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the great powers were fighting to bear the costs of the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved more aggressively to bring the countries with a very high greenhouse gas levy to account for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will develop a new economic dominance, said Ulate, who is also a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change reported that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will at best lead to a political agreement.
The alliance of the small island states with 43 members presented a 24-page draft treaty in the early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who is head of the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states "puts political pressure on the whole political process," partly because they are now united and demand measures from emerging countries such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency when the delegates focused on the fact that most of the open issues had to be resolved before the government leaders arrived in order to reach an agreement.
High-level representatives, such as the Indian Environment Minister Jaimam Ramesh and the Chinese Vice-Minister, escaped their aircraft and raced through the Bella Center's corridors to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to set off claims that will be negotiated during the next week.
The sheer extent of the meeting -- 13,000 people go to and from the Congress Centre every day, gitar-playing activists are holding night shows in which they make fun of the countries that they think betray and sell, and draft contracts are passed on by hand instead of by e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all important ministers are now here and from Wednesday, 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We come to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy of the Organization Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
