The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, report Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was in a dry zone of the Pangaea supercontinent at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of the dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging on the Ghost Ranch in the north of New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by the researchers as new species.
In the course of the excavation, they brought together the remains of five individuals.
Found confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare, usually only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
After the present teaching opinion, the dinosaurs first showed up about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the assignment of these original dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the lizards split into their three main development lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and the birds, which were known as the "long-legged" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plant-eating ornithichia (bird-basin-sauri), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropode.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
At the head of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, as they also own the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of the mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropode with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge sauropods later also had air bags and light-building bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
As a result, the three lines of development split up early and spread from South America over all parts of the world, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent of Pangaa.
The fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not very closely related theropods.
The three cannot come from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of the dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says the Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be a distorted picture, because in South America, a great many primitive Dino fossils have just been preserved, while on other continents there is little to be found.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare side line of the reptile stem to the dominant farmers of the Middle Ages, is still mysterious.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the air-hauliers and with numerous other lizards.
At the end of the Trias, the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the relationship on the border from the Trias to the Jura died out.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteor impact of a group of animals, which had also developed in the Trias and has since been in a dark state, has helped to flourish: the mammals.
