The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief doctor of the General Psychiatry Clinic in Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the event, everything has a meaning for it.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he is, like in the dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot make them active.
Schizophrenes therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A balance of reality is usually not possible for them, the trugpictures are cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
To have experienced a hallucination once in life
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in the psychosis, is in principle preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real context.
Why exactly our brain is beating capriols, researchers are still facing a mystery.
Exceptional conditions can lead to a short-term loss of reality in every person, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in the case of those affected.
We suspect that the neural maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example, by a mother's viral disease during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But there remains a mystery about how the disturbance of the neural system comes about, which, in addition, does not manifest itself for many years at first.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the cause of a psychosis when the disposition is present.
Also hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis as they intervene in the transmitter system.
When our brain is running hot
