It is often only a question of the position whether tru-images are felt to be pleasant or unpleasant.
For ten years, Kastel has been collecting reports of hallucinations and truders, and last year he has evaluated his results in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head."
Hallucinations are among the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of amazing many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's and brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain is hallucinating healthy people.
Hallucinations, according to the box, are made up of memory contents that are normally held back.
They occur when brain areas where sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is missing.
Drugs can cause this condition as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the attraction, stress, love, or other mental states of exception.
