Boundary state between dream and hallucination
In our too consciousness-centered world, imaginary experience is, unfortunately, pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, suffering disease, but it also contains positive, creative - delusion is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of traumically changed consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the living person considers real and which he cannot, in retrospect, distinguish from the state of wax.
The oneiroid state of consciousness is created in extreme traumatic or disease-related situations, for example in polyradikulitis patients who are fully aware of motor paralysis.
