75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among the younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fertility and career of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market as being limited due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to set up a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and if so, what kind of work they do.
Those of them who do no other job outside the house, work only half-day or have no fixed contract of employment, become more mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a fixed job, especially in the public sector, are postponing the establishment of a family and maternity and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the 35-49 age group with a fixed job receive their first child on average only 3.7 years after the date of the move together, a figure which increases to 4.1 years for women with a fixed job who have taken longer to achieve this and who have moved together and the first child have only realized much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a great influence on motherhood, though less than the calendar in terms of the willingness to receive a conception, "explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference was also found in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between 35 and 49 years, depending on whether they have only primary or higher education, became mother for the first time, on average, at 25.1 or 32.1.
There is also a further difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with a master's degree get married before their first permanent job and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree do it exactly the other way around and first seek a permanent job and get married and then get their first child, Delgado notes.
