Support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock braking system and as is now the case with the stability control ESP, the emergency braking systems must be a compulsory release in European cars.
In fact, they are already required for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, and for the remaining vehicles a waiting period was fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measures adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent a lot of road accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake manoeuvre, which the system recognizes by the driver's braking strength on the brake pedal.
However, this system does not exercise this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even get to the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not stopped with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car passes during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents that damage pedestrians could be avoided every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistance.
There would be even fewer accidents - one is expected to prevent one in four accidents with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that recognizes obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, and at the same time it already has a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if it is necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant exercises the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
